The WP budget enables ODG/EVA to conduct thematic, impact and country level evaluations, to implement activities jointly with other UN agencies and to contribute to the strengthening of monitoring and evaluation capacities of counterpart ministries. During the present biennium there is a large increase in mandatory project evaluations and a need to complement ODG/EVA staff resources with consultancy services to be able to manage, GEF terminal evaluations and to ensure that UNIDO is aligned to the GEF evaluation policy and its fiduciary standards.

Preparation for HCFC phase-out investment activities (stage II)
(refrigeration and air-conditioning manufacturing sector)
The objective of the HPMP - Stage II is to develop the second stage of a Compliance Strategy and corresponding Action Plan for the substances controlled under Annex C Group I (HCFCs) of the Montreal Protocol, for the period 2015 to 2020, such that the consumption of HCFCs is reduced by 35% from the baseline.

The objective of the survey is be to assist the country to better understand its consumption trends for non-ODS alternatives, and their distribution by sector and subsector. The inventory on ODS alternatives may also provide the country with an overview of their national market where ODS alternatives have been (and will be) phased in, while taking into consideration existing technologies. The survey will estimate the amounts of each ODS alternative currently used in the country, identify alternatives that could be potentially used in the future to replace HCFCs and HFCs; and forecast the amounts of each of the ODS alternatives currently used and potentially to be used in the country for the 2015-2030 period.

In the post WTO globalised market place, specific concerns have been raised that developing countries are not deriving the potential benefits from globalization. While markets are made “open” and “free”, developing countries have to overcome many obstacles to reap the potential rewards. A key challenge facing developing countries is the lack of national capacity to comply with the WTO Technical Barriers to Trade (TBT) and Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) agreement requirements, which are now global trade embedded market requirements.

In order to meet this challenge, developing countries need significant technical assistance to establish a National Quality System (NQS) and develop institutional infrastructure related to Standards, Metrology, Testing, and Quality (SMTQ); in order to be an able partner in the global trade regime.
Sierra Leone has been a member of WTO since 23 July 1995. However, the country does not dispose of a National Quality Policy; a well developed Competent Authority for fisheries to ensure the quality and safety of the exported fishery products which is one of the major exports of the country or basic capabilities for micro-biological and chemical testing of products and facilities for equipment calibration for ensuring the accuracy of measurement. As a consequence of the non-existence such infrastructure
local population is at various risks through imported sub-standard products whilst exports are inevitably more difficult and the country is thus not in a position to meet the EU export requirements for fisheries and capitalize on this area of exports which is an important trade flow for developing
countries around the world.

This project will focus on
a) Supporting the development of a National Quality Policy
b) Supporting the development of a Competent Authority for fisheries exports and
c) Upgrading and development of the national testing laboratory infrastructure with respect to chemical, microbiological, metrology/calibration laboratories.
